      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Hiram Smith (1814-1888) was a 19th century farmer, sash manufacturer and house builder in upstate New York.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Hiram Smith Collection</emph> contains memorabilia, printed material and writings.</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Memorabilia</emph> contains an undated photograph of Smith; written on the back are the words, 
		 "Hiram Smith b. 1814 d. 1888 (Fred's g. grandfather)".</p>
		 <p><emph render="bold">Printed material</emph> consists of a copy of The Courier, Vol. 34, containing an article about 
		 Smith and several sheets of biographical and genealogical information about Hiram and the Smith family, provided by his 
		 grand-daughter Edna Crocker Smith, who donated the collection.</p>		 
		 <p><emph render="bold">Writings</emph> contains the complete handwritten manuscript of Smith's autobiography, entitled 
		 "A Memoir of the Life of Hiram Smith."  The account, which begins with his birth in 1814 and ends in 1874, includes 
		 reminiscences of learning to play the violin, travels all over central New York via the Erie Canal, and making a sled 
		 out of a pig's lower jaw.  His account is unusually interesting and valuable because he mentions by name many of the 
		 people and places he visited, and offers a vivid and fascinating window into life in upstate New York in the early 
		 part of the 19th century.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
